===Etymology===
1437, from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|funerailles||funeral rites|g=p}}, from {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{m|la|fūnerālia||funeral rites}}, originally neuter plural of {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{m|la|fūnerālis||having to do with a funeral}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|fūnus||funeral, death, corpse}}, origin unknown, perhaps ultimately from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*dʰew-||to die}}. Singular and plural used interchangeably in English until circa 1700. The adjective {{m|en|funereal}} is first attested 1725, by influence of {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|funerail}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|funereus}}, from {{m|la|funus}}.

